titleStmt.title: Cambridge, Cambridge University Library, MS Add.1117

respStmt.resp: Edited by Michael Marx in collaboration with Tobias J. Jocham et. al. TEI version created by Yasmin Faghihi and Huw Jones

summary.p: 54 folios; Writing surface: parchment; Shelfmark: MS Add.1117; Qurʾānic text: Q 3:117-197; 6 Lines per page; Dimensions: 160 x 105 mm; Script style: kūfī D II; Estimated date of production: 9th or 10th century AD /3rd or 4th century Hijri.

Fragment of an Abbasid Qur'ān probably written in the third or fourth century A.H. / ninth or tenth century C.E, containing verses 117-197 from the Sura Āl ʿImrān (سورة آل عمران). Folios 13, 18, 47 and 48 of this manuscript (numbered from fol. 1 to fol. 58) are missing. For more information about the manuscript, see the entry in the Digital Library of Cambridge University.

The University of Cambridge acquired the fragment in 1878 from Edward H. Palmer (1840-1882) and E.E. Tyrwhitt Drake. The displayed fragment and other early Qur'an manuscripts (call numbers Add.1115 - Add.1150) were acquired by Palmer during a research trip to the Sinai Peninsula (cf. Ansorge 2016).
